subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
This species differs from other species by having the apical third of the clypeus, mandible, palpi, scape, pedicel, flagellum, and legs mostly yellowish brown (
Figs 3A, 3B
); the frons densely and finely punctate (
Fig. 3A
); and the gena in dorsal view strongly receding posteriorly (
Fig. 3F
) in the female; and metasomal tergum I not petiolate but gradually narrowed anteriorly in the male (
Fig. 4A
).

Description.
(Measurements of the 
holotype
are given in parentheses.) FEMALE. Length: body 4.2–6.8 (5.6) mm; fore wing 4.1–6.2 (4.7) mm. Body black and polished (metasoma more strongly polished than others) (
Fig. 3B
); mesoscutum and scutellum with weak metallic-blue luster. Following yellowish-brown: apical third of clypeus (
Fig. 3A
), mandible (reddish-brown apically), palpi, scape, pedicel, flagellum below and all legs except outer and dorsal faces of coxae (
Fig. 3B
). Following bright brown to castaneous: flagellum dorsally, tegula (
Fig. 3C
), outer and dorsal faces of coxae, lateral and posterior margins of pronotum and metasomal terga, and posterior margins of sterna. Wings (
Fig. 3D
) hyaline with yellowish tint.

Head width 1.1–1.2 (1.1) × length. Vertex in frontal view moderately convex (
Fig. 3A
). Inner orbits slightly convergent above, subparallel below (
Fig. 3A
). UID: MID: LID = 7.0–8.1 (7.6): 10: 9.1–9.5 (9.5). MID 0.57– 0.63 (0.60) × head width. Frons in profile gently convex, slightly protruding anteriorly, a little exceeding level of clypeus (
Fig. 3E
); frontal line impressed only below (
Fig. 3A
). Gena width in profile 0.6–0.8 (0.6) × eye width (
Fig. 3E
). Ocellar triangle acute-angled (
Fig. 3F
), slightly raised. POL: OOL = 1: 0.72–1.8 (0.94). Clypeus as broad as LID (
Fig. 3A
), its width 2.3–2.7 (2.6) × length, convex medially; apicolateral corner broadly rounded; apical rim slightly depressed and alutaceous; apical margin broadly straight. Malar space very short. Flagellomere I length 1.3–1.4 (1.3) × flagellomere II length, 4.5–5.9 (5.2) × its width, 0.74–1.0 (0.84) × UID.

Pronotum slightly depressed near posterior margin, latter being obtusely angulate medially (
Figs 3C, 3F
); anterior declivity not distinctly differentiated from dorsum; shoulder scarcely bulging. Discs of scutellum and metanotum slightly convex above level of mesoscutum. Metapostnotum length 0.1–0.2 (0.2) × metanotum length at midline. Propodeum length 0.85–1.1 (1.0) × width, gently and evenly convex in profile (
Fig. 3B
); medial groove shallow and indistinct, if any.

Metasomal tergum I with long petiole (
Fig. 3C
). Tergum II width 0.83–0.99 (0.88) × head width.

Head width in frontal view 1.1–1.2 × length. UID: MID: LID = 8.0–8.6: 10: 8.7–9.1. MID 0.59–0.61 × head width. Ocellar triangle right- to obtuse-angled (
Fig. 4C
). POL: OOL = 1: 0.74–1.0. Clypeus width 2.3–2.4 × length. Gena in dorsal view more roundly receding than in female (compare 
Fig. 4C
with 
Fig. 3F
), its width in profile 0.6–0.7 × eye width (
Fig. 4D
). Flagellomere I length 0.95–0.98 × flagellomere II length, 2.5–2.9 × its width and 0.58–0.68 × UID.

Pronotum with shoulder roundly receding anteriorly (
Fig. 4C
); sides overall convergent anteriorly. Discs of scutellum and metanotum more strongly raised than in female (
Fig. 4E
). Metapostnotum length 0.2–0.3 × metanotum length at midline. Propodeum length 0.85–0.87 × width.

Metasomal sternum II with transverse groove slightly arcuate, situated close to posterior margin of tergum I. A pair of lateral hooks on sternum VI tapering and directed outward apically with several erect setae basally (
Fig. 4H
). Posterior margin of sternum VI between hooks slightly and arcuately emarginate. Exposed portion of SGP (
Fig. 4H
) with fluke on side, that being directed posterolaterally, and with long dense setae subapically and apically; apical margin subangularly produced. Genitalia (

Figs 
4I
, 4J

): paramere extending slightly beyond apex of aedeagus with long dense setae on outer face from base to apex.
